prompt:
Use Three.js to implement a robot disassembly simulator. Load the external robot.glb model, support disassembling the robot's main parts (head, torso, left arm, right arm, legs) into an exploded view, and support a reassembly animation.

[Three.js Import (must follow strictly)]
Add the following importmap in <head>, and import via ES Module in <script type="module">:
<script type="importmap">
{ "imports": {
    "three": "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.170.0/build/three.module.js",
    "three/addons/": "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.170.0/examples/jsm/"
} }
</script>
<script type="module">
import * as THREE from 'three';
import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/addons/loaders/GLTFLoader.js';
import { OrbitControls } from 'three/addons/controls/OrbitControls.js';
// Your code here
</script>

[Model Loading]
(1) Load assets/robot.glb using GLTFLoader;
(2) Center the model at the scene origin and scale appropriately after loading;
(3) After loading, set window.__3D_STATE__.modelLoaded = true;
(4) Traverse the model's child nodes, identify the main parts and group them into 5 groups: head, torso, leftArm, rightArm, legs. Group by child node name or position;

[OrbitControls]
(5) Use OrbitControls for camera orbit;

[Disassembly]
(6) Add a "Disassemble" button (id="disassembleBtn") on the page;
(7) Clicking "Disassemble" flies the 5 parts out to exploded view positions in their respective directions (head up, leftArm left, rightArm right, torso forward, legs down), using lerp or tween animation for smooth transition over ~1 second;
(8) After disassembly, set window.__3D_STATE__.assemblyState = 'disassembled';

[Part Selection]
(9) In exploded view, use Raycaster to click any part to select it;
(10) Selected part shows highlight effect (emissive glow or outline);
(11) Display the selected part's name and description in a fixed info panel on the right side (id="partInfoPanel"):
  - head: "Head" — "Contains visual sensors and processing unit";
  - torso: "Torso" — "Main structural frame and power core";
  - leftArm: "Left Arm" — "Equipped with precision grasping end-effector";
  - rightArm: "Right Arm" — "Equipped with multi-function tool interface";
  - legs: "Legs" — "Bipedal walking mechanism and balance system";
(12) Update window.__3D_STATE__.selectedPart to the selected part name string; null when nothing is selected;

[Assembly]
(13) Add an "Assemble" button (id="assembleBtn") on the page;
(14) Clicking "Assemble" smoothly animates all parts back to their original positions over ~1 second;
(15) After assembly, set window.__3D_STATE__.assemblyState = 'assembled';

[HUD Display]
(16) Top-left HUD panel (semi-transparent background) shows:
  - Assembly state (id="assemblyStatus", shows 'assembled' / 'disassembled' / 'animating');
  - Currently selected part (id="selectedPartName", shows part name or "None");
  - Animation progress (id="animProgress", shows 0%-100%);
  - Model load status (id="loadStatus");

[Visual Effects]
(17) Scene background: deep blue gradient (0x1a1a2e);
(18) Add DirectionalLight + AmbientLight + HemisphereLight for industrial lighting;
(19) Optional: add a ground grid for reference;

[State Exposure (required)]
Update window.__3D_STATE__ every frame:
  - modelLoaded: boolean (whether model has finished loading)
  - assemblyState: string ('assembled' | 'disassembled' | 'animating')
  - selectedPart: string | null (currently selected part: 'head'/'torso'/'leftArm'/'rightArm'/'legs' or null)
  - animationProgress: number (animation progress 0-1)
  - partCount: number (total number of parts, should be 5)
  - cameraDistance: number (camera distance to origin)

Output a single self-contained HTML file. Place the file and the assets/ folder in the same directory; serve via a local HTTP server.
